% \section{Memoization}
% This package supports externalization via the \refPkg{memoize} package.
%
% In principle, the individual pictures generated by this package are quite simple and fast to draw.
% However, once a document contains lots of these pictures, externalization can significantly improve the compilation time of a document.
% To give you numbers on that: a document with around 450 \refEnv{step}s took me about \qty{15}{\second} to compile.
% With the use of \refPkg{memoize}, the compilation time reduced to about \qty{4}{\second} (all measurements done with Lua\LaTeX and only measuring the final run).
% But keep in mind, externalization often leads to more compilation cycles.
% Thus, you need to evaluate for your individual setting whether externalization makes sense for you.
%
% When \refPkg{memoize} is loaded, this package automatically sets up memoization for \refEnv{step}s.
% Still, you may need to perform a few actions (such as install a library and make \refPkg{memoize} use it) to make memoization work which are described in \refPkg{memoize}'s documentation.
% Also note that \refPkg{memoize} should always be \emph{loaded before this package}.
%
% \subsection{Where the memoize integration reaches its limits}
% All styles and presets defined by this package are set up so that changes result in updates of the generated externs.
% But this reaches its limits when you start defining and using your own styles.
% For example the example given in \cref{sec:presets:custom} would not lead to an update when e.g. the style \texttt{myPreset} is being modified.
% This can lead to confusion when modifications are not reflected in the output.
% It can also lead to unexpected behavior when modifying the style mid-document.
% For such cases you'll need to familiarize yourself with the \refPkg{memoize} package and learn how to make your customizations memoization-aware.
%
%
% \subsection{Advice when to enable memoization}
% Personally, I use the following strategy.
% Generally, I activate \refPkg{memoize}.
% While working on the document, I use the \texttt{readonly} option of \emph{memoize}.
% This way, no new externs are generated and I avoid increasing compilation time by the requirement of additional compilation cycles.
% Still, compilation is sped up by the externs which were previously generated.
% Then, after work is finished, I compile without the \texttt{readonly} option to generate the externs for next time.
%
% Note, \refPkg{memoize} recommends disabling it when generating the final version of the document or more generally, a version which gets released.
%
% \MaybeStop{}
%
% \section{Implementation}
% \iffalse
%<*package>
% \fi
%    \begin{macrocode}
\RequirePackage{pgfkeys}
\RequirePackage{pgfopts}
\RequirePackage{coloredbelts}
\RequirePackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{calc,positioning,fit,arrows.meta}
\usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings,decorations.pathmorphing,backgrounds}
%    \end{macrocode}
%
% Define marginline in case it isn't already defined (so the package works without KOMA-classes as well).
%    \begin{macrocode}
\AddToHook {begindocument} [kata/provideMarginline] {%
  \providecommand\marginline[1]{%
    \marginpar[{\raggedleft #1}]{\raggedright #1}%
  }%
}
%    \end{macrocode}
%
% Define own string compare for equality so the package works without KOMA as well.
%    \begin{macrocode}
\ExpandArgs {nnc} \UseName {cs_set_eq:NN} {\kata@ifstr} {str_if_eq:eeTF}
%    \end{macrocode}
